
 DATE:23/12/2025                                                                 MODULES

In Python, a module is simply a file that contains Python code (functions, variables, classes) and has a .py extension. When you import that file in another Python file, you can reuse everything defined inside it.
‚Äã

Basic idea
A module is just one .py file, for example math_utils.py.
It is used to organize code so that it is easier to maintain and reuse instead of writing everything in a single big file.
You bring a module‚Äôs code into another file using the import or from ... import ... statements.

‚ÄãSyntax to use a module
1Ô∏è‚É£ Import the whole module
import module_name

module_name.function()

2Ô∏è‚É£ Import specific items
from module_name import function1, function2

3Ô∏è‚É£ Import with alias
import module_name as alias


Types of Modules in Python

Python modules are mainly of three types:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Built-in Modules
2Ô∏è‚É£ User-defined Modules
3Ô∏è‚É£ Third-party (External) Modules

1Ô∏è‚É£ Built-in Modules

These come pre-installed with Python. You don‚Äôt need to install them.

 Examples: math, random, datetime, os, sys

üîπ Example: random module
import random

print(random.randint(1, 10))


 Gives a random number between 1 and 10.

üîπ Example: datetime module
import datetime

today = datetime.datetime.now()
print(today)

2Ô∏è‚É£ User-defined Modules

These are modules you create yourself in a .py file to reuse your code.

 Example: Create calc.py

# calc.py
def add(a, b):
    return a + b

def sub(a, b):
    return a - b


Use it in another file:

import calc

print(calc.add(10, 5))
print(calc.sub(10, 5))

3Ô∏è‚É£ Third-party (External) Modules

These are created by others and must be installed using pip.

 Examples: numpy, pandas, requests, matplotlib

üîπ Install first (in terminal):
pip install requests

üîπ Example: requests module
import requests

response = requests.get("https://api.github.com")
print(response.status_code)